## Relationship with the Terms of Service (EULA)

> This Privacy Policy and the Terms of Service (EULA) are complementary: this Policy focuses on personal data; the EULA covers rights and obligations, risk allocation, disclaimers and dispute resolution—please read both. If you leave Japan Receipt Helper and open another app for maps or turn‑by‑turn navigation, location‑ or device‑related handling in **that third‑party application** falls primarily under that provider’s privacy terms; see also Article 9 of the EULA.


## 1. What information do we collect (scope of data collection)

- **Identifiers and login data**: If you authenticate with Sign in with Apple or another OAuth issuer, identifiers created or referenced by Supabase Authentication (such as emails or provider IDs—depending on issuer settings), display names, locale, and currency preferences.

- **Common identity fields that are not collected separately at the registration level**: This application does not set ID card number, birthday, phone number, detailed address, etc. as required registration fields, nor does it actively ask you to provide such information for account verification. If words such as name or phone number appear in user content such as accounting and receipt recognition, it comes from the image or the record content you input yourself, and is not a separate field collected for identity registration.

- **User-generated content and feature-derived data**: ledger rows (line items, amounts, dates, categories, merchant names, etc.); text or structured content produced after receipt imagery is recognised (which may expose whatever appears on the slip). Receipt recognition runs on our backend using third‑party cloud services (including one or more cooperating AI / image‑recognition vendors). **For each OCR request, imagery sent to those vendors is processed within that request's lifecycle and we do not attach your member display name, email, or similar OAuth identifiers as outbound labels or folder markers** (request identity stays segregated on our servers). Contracts require cooperating vendors **not to use that imagery—or content not properly anonymised—for model training, fine‑tuning, or unrelated commercial reuse**; transient storage on their side is governed by their technical documents and contracts. Ledger map pins: coordinates come from textual addresses via geocoding handled by cooperating map / geocoder partners. GPS / precise location permission is never requested and no handset GPS breadcrumbs are persisted.

- **Operating system permissions for camera, photo library (album/gallery) and file access**: Only when you actively use functions that require shooting, selecting images from the photo library/album, or importing files (such as receipt image recognition, accounting, and the selection or production of thumbnails/screenshots/shared images related to accounting maps, or other related functions you enable), you will be asked for authorization according to the system prompts, and used for the images or file content required for the operation. We do not use the camera to record videos in the background, record secrets, or access the camera screen or photo album when you are not operating the relevant functions.

- **Technical data and connection information**: When you use this service, within the scope required for normal connection and information security, infrastructure or server logs may include IP address, connection/request time and number, User-Agent (which can reflect the browser or App execution environment, operating system version, etc.); sensor data is only processed on the device side according to the operating system authorization when you use functions that require hardware permissions such as cameras; this application does not create separate sensor data profiles for marketing or tracking purposes. Regarding advertising identifiers (e.g., Apple IDFA): we currently do **not** embed broadly used behavioural‑analytics or ad‑network SDKs. If you complete in‑App purchases or interact with Apple App Store or RevenueCat, those providers inevitably process transactional identifiers—their contractual and privacy frameworks govern.

- **Precise/real-time location (GPS)**: This app does **not** request GPS or precise‑location permission, does **not** collect or store handset GPS readings, and does **not** build a breadcrumb trail of your movements in real time. Map pins reflect text such as merchants and addresses derived from bookkeeping or receipts, converted to coordinates by geocoding. We **do not** derive positions from embedded photo metadata such as EXIF, nor assemble a mobility history from handset live location.

- **Local and cache data**: Settings such as interface language and preferred currency (local currency conversion) may live in Local Storage on your device. **Japan prefecture “conquest” visit records** sync to Supabase alongside your signed‑in profile, with an optional device copy for faster loading. **Guest mode** data may remain on‑device until you sign in, then merges into your cloud account.


## 2. How we collect information (collection method)

- **Voluntary submission**: credentials issued after Sign in with Apple / OAuth approvals; handwritten ledger edits; uploads from camera / library / importer when you intentionally run OCR.

- **Automatic logging and forwarding**: When you use the app (e.g. saving ledger rows or syncing), the client sends minimally necessary payloads to our entrusted cloud. To enable recognition or geocoding the backend forwards text or imagery to cooperating OCR / AI / geospatial stacks **strictly for that operation**—without unnecessary account identifiers as labels on cooperating systems. See Sections 1 and 5.

- **Cookie/terminal storage**: If you access the web version with a browser, the server can send session or security cookies according to standard protocols; the application uses Local Storage and other storage interface settings and preferences, not for the purpose of tracking cross-domain advertising analysis.


## 3. Why do we need this information (purpose of use)

- **Provide and maintain core functions**: bookkeeping, FX and currencies, ledger map pins, receipt image recognition, travel tips/guides, badges and membership tiers, etc.

- **Identity and security**: Confirm login identity, prevent abuse, and save your information under the account.

- **Product improvement**: De-identify/aggregate accounting and other data before statistical or model improvements are made, and the original details that can identify you will not be disclosed to the public.

- **Third-party models and marketing**: Aside from narrowly scoped subcontractors working under our instructions to deliver a requested feature in the smallest necessary way, we **do not** provide identifiable personal data to third parties so they may train, fine‑tune or optimise ML or generative models, nor for cold outreach, surveys, audience building or list resale. Receipt‑**OCR** partners must **not** exploit batches of slips for **model training or fine‑tuning**. Payloads routed through cooperating services remain limited to the invoked function and are subject to those providers’ terms **and this Policy.**

- **Legal Compliance and Disputes**: Necessary processing to cooperate with the competent authorities or claims of rights within the scope permitted by law.

- Your personal information is not sold to data intermediaries or used in a manner that is obviously inconsistent with the stated purpose; if there is any marketing or promotion in the future, prior consent will be obtained in accordance with the law or may be refused at any time, and the withdrawal method will be stated in the application or in a visible place.


## 4. How to store and protect data (security)

- **Storage location**: Personal data and the content you supply are hosted mainly by Supabase’s cloud database plus related compute/storage strata; hosted **region(s)** appear in Supabase’s public posture statements.

- **Hosting environment and third-party certification (reference)**: According to Supabase’s public statement, its hosting platform has passed independent audits (including SOC 2 Type 2) and obtained information security management certifications such as ISO 27001. Actual exposure and protection are still affected by project settings, access control, and the shared responsibility model between suppliers and customers. For details, see Supabase’s official security and compliance documents.

- **Transmission and encryption**: External connections preferentially use encrypted channels commonly used in the industry such as TLS/HTTPS; database and identity authentication are handled by Supabase in accordance with its security design and our access control settings. However, Internet transmission may still be affected by factors such as terminal devices, user networks (including public Wi-Fi), malicious programs or settings, so there is no guarantee that any transmission path will be absolutely free from third-party eavesdropping or tampering under any circumstances; please understand this together with the description of security measures in this chapter and elsewhere in this policy.

- **De-identification**: Aggregated/de-identified data used for statistical or model training purposes, which have been removed or irreversibly de-identified, are subject to this chapter and the aforementioned purpose of use description.

- **Summary of retention period**: Please also refer to "9. Data Retention and Deletion". After the account is deleted, in principle, the content linked to the account will be removed from the operating environment within a reasonable period of no more than approximately thirty (30) days (this does not apply to those that are required to be temporarily retained by law or have been anonymized).


